# Linux Fundamentals

## What is Linux?

Linux is a **free and open-source operating system (OS)** based on Unix.

Unlike proprietary operating systems such as **Windows** and **macOS**, Linux gives users full control over the system and allows anyone to view, modify, and distribute its source code.


## Key Features of Linux

### 🔓 Fully Open-Source
- Source code is publicly available.
- Anyone can inspect, modify, and contribute to the project.

### 💻 Multi-Platform
- Runs on desktops, laptops, servers, smartphones, embedded devices, and supercomputers.

### ⚙️ Highly Customizable & Lightweight
- Users can customize nearly every aspect of the operating system.
- Can run efficiently on both modern and older hardware.

### 🛡️ Secure & Stable
- Strong permission system and security model.
- Widely used in servers due to its reliability and uptime.

### 🤝 Community-Driven
- Supported by a large global community of developers and contributors.
- Extensive documentation and learning resources are available.

### 🧠 Kernel-Based
- The Linux Kernel is the core component that manages hardware and system resources.
- Different Linux distributions use the same kernel with different tools and interfaces.


# Why Learn Linux?

### 🏢 Industry Standard
- Dominates servers, cloud platforms, and enterprise infrastructure.

### 🚀 Career Opportunities
- Essential skill for Cybersecurity, DevOps, Cloud Computing, System Administration, and Software Development.

### 🔒 Security & Stability
- Trusted by organizations for critical systems and infrastructure.

### 🎨 Customizable
- Freedom to tailor the operating system to specific needs.

### ⚡ Efficient
- Performs well even on low-resource hardware.


# Popular Linux Distributions

## Debian-Based Distributions

| Distribution | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| Ubuntu | Beginner-friendly and widely used Linux distribution |
| Kali Linux | Designed for penetration testing and security assessments |
| Linux Mint | User-friendly distribution based on Ubuntu |
| Parrot OS | Security-focused distribution for pentesting and development |
| Kali Purple | Combines Red Team and Blue Team security tools |


## Red Hat-Based Distributions

| Distribution | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) | Enterprise-grade commercial Linux distribution |
| Fedora Linux | Community-driven distribution sponsored by Red Hat |
| Rocky Linux | Free RHEL-compatible enterprise distribution |
| AlmaLinux | Community-supported RHEL replacement |
| CentOS | Historically a free RHEL-based distribution |


## Arch-Based Distributions

| Distribution | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| Arch Linux | Minimal, highly customizable Linux distribution |
| Manjaro | User-friendly distribution based on Arch Linux |


## SUSE-Based Distributions

| Distribution | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| openSUSE | Community-supported Linux distribution |
| SUSE Linux Enterprise | Enterprise version of SUSE Linux |


## Other Distributions

| Distribution | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| Gentoo | Source-based Linux distribution with maximum customization |
| Slackware | One of the oldest Linux distributions, known for simplicity and stability |


## Quick Summary

- Linux is a **free and open-source operating system**.
- The **Linux Kernel** is the core component of every Linux distribution.
- Linux is widely used in **Cybersecurity, Cloud Computing, Servers, DevOps, and System Administration**.
- Different distributions are designed for different purposes, but all use the Linux Kernel.
